{"id": "2877375", "revid": "7186", "url": "https://en.wikinews.org/wiki?curid=2877375", "title": "Wikinews interviews 2020 US Libertarian Party presidential candidate Adam Kokesh", "text": ", an Iraq War veteran, activist, radio show host, and currently a candidate for the US Libertarian Party's 2020 presidential nomination, spoke with \"Wikinews\" to discuss his background, political positions, and campaign for President of the United States.\nKokesh, who hails from Arizona, has been active in the movement since returning home from combat in Iraq. After an initial honorary discharge from active duty with the in 2006, Kokesh was given a general discharge from the in 2007 after images of him wearing his uniform while participating in a protest with the were published in \"The Washington Post\". Kokesh has also been involved in demonstrations in support of free speech, gun rights, and . Some of these activities have resulted in his arrest. Kokesh previously hosted a show on and currently hosts a show on .\nPolitically, Kokesh supported the and of Ron Paul. He was a featured speaker at Paul's in 2008. Kokesh ran for US Congress as a Republican in 2010 in New Mexico and for US Senate in . He announced his 2020 candidacy in 2013 during a jailhouse interview. He has based his campaign on the pledge to begin \"dissolving the federal government in a peaceful, orderly manner\" and to resign as president and take the title of \"Custodian of the Federal Government.\" \nOther contenders for the Libertarian Party's 2020 presidential nomination include former Libertarian Party Vice Chairman , businessman , and New Hampshire state representative . Congressman and former Rhode Island governor and US Senator are both reportedly considering runs. Former New York gubernatorial candidate and former Massachusetts governor William Weld were both previously considered potential candidates but Sharpe suggested he would not run and Weld has decided to run in the , challenging President Donald Trump.\nWith accredited \"Wikinews\" reporter William S. Saturn, Kokesh details his background and activism, his thoughts on the Libertarian Party, the Presidency of Donald Trump, and the goals for his campaign and presidency. \nInterview.\nBackground &amp; activism.\nWhich presidential candidates have you supported and/or voted for in previous election cycles during your lifetime?\nWhich historical or contemporary figures do you admire and consider as role models? Why?\nAt what point during your time in Iraq did you realize the effort there was immoral?\nIn what ways do you believe you have accomplished what you have sought through activism? In what ways have you failed?\nOn the Libertarian Party.\nWhy did you join the Libertarian Party?\nIn 2016, the Libertarian Party's presidential nominee Gary Johnson received 3.28 percent of the popular vote, the most of any previous Libertarian presidential nominee. What can you do as the party's nominee to increase the vote share? \nWhat are your thoughts on your fellow candidates and potential candidates for the Libertarian Party's 2020 presidential nomination, specifically, former Vice Chairman Arvin Vohra, former New York gubernatorial candidate Larry Sharpe, and former Massachusetts Governor William Weld?\nOn the presidency of Donald Trump.\nWhat qualities of President Donald Trump and his presidency do you admire? What qualities do you despise?\nWhat actions of President Trump do you support? What actions do you disapprove?\nGoals.\nAs President Trump learned early in his presidency, federal courts can effectively nullify controversial executive orders. If you are elected president, what will you do in the event a federal court rules your executive order creating a process to dissolve the federal government as unconstitutional?\nOn your website you state \"American troops abroad will be immediately brought home in a responsible and orderly manner that does not endanger their lives.\" The qualifier \"responsible\" has been used previously to justify an indefinite military presence. Can you clarify what you mean by a \"responsible and orderly manner\" of withdrawal?\nWhat has led you to the conclusion that running for president is the best way to spread your message over other avenues?"}
